<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    Where the Chapter 09 module's filter is EMPTY because every type defends its representation, this
    module deliberately ships two counter-examples whose contract violations ARE the lesson, so
    a test can prove the failure the prose describes rather than merely assert it. The detectors are
    left fully ENABLED for the rest of the module (Order, Money, Catalog, OrderBook all stay clean);
    only these two named classes carry a finding, and each is suppressed narrowly, with a reason, and
    pointed at the test that demonstrates why it matters. Removing either class — or fixing it — is the
    real advice; the suppression exists so the teaching counter-example can ship green.
  -->

  <!--
    BrokenPrice overrides equals() but inherits Object.hashCode(), so two value-equal instances hash
    to different buckets and a HashMap "loses" a key it contains. Proven by
    ImmutabilityContractTest#hashMapLosesAKeyWhenHashCodeIsNotOverridden. The fix is to derive both
    contracts by making the type a record (Money), never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.immutability.BrokenPrice"/>
    <Bug pattern="HE_EQUALS_USE_HASHCODE"/>
  </Match>

  <!--
    OrderLeaky stores the caller's list directly and returns the internal list, so a caller can mutate
    the "immutable" order through either reference (EI_EXPOSE_REP2 on store, EI_EXPOSE_REP on return) —
    the hook's bug. Proven by ImmutabilityContractTest#leakyOrderChangesItsMindWhenTheCallerMutatesTheList.
    The fix is the defensive copy in Order's compact constructor, never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.immutability.OrderLeaky"/>
    <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP,EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
